<ArticleLayout
  title="Living Room Storage Ideas for Everyday Australian Homes"
  description="Practical living room storage ideas for Australian homes, apartments and family spaces, including baskets, media storage, toy storage, blankets, books and everyday clutter."
  category="Living Spaces"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  image="/images/living-room.webp"
  imageAlt="A warm living room with tidy storage, soft seating and natural light"
>
  <p>
    The living room is often the most-used room in the home. It may be where people watch TV,
    relax, read, play with pets, spend time with children, entertain guests or work from a
    laptop. Because it serves so many purposes, it can also become one of the hardest rooms to
    keep organised.
  </p>
  <p>
    A good living room storage setup does not need to hide every sign of real life. The aim is
    to make everyday items easy to use, easy to put away and less likely to spread across the
    room. In Australian homes, this can be especially useful in apartments, townhouses and
    open-plan living areas where storage is limited.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide covers practical living room storage ideas worth considering for everyday
    Australian households.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with what the room is actually used for</h2>
  <p>
    Before buying storage products, look at how the living room is used day to day.
  </p>
  <p>Common living room uses include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Watching TV.</li>
    <li>Relaxing after work.</li>
    <li>Reading.</li>
    <li>Children's play.</li>
    <li>Pet time.</li>
    <li>Entertaining guests.</li>
    <li>Working from a laptop.</li>
    <li>Storing blankets, remotes and chargers.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A living room used by a family with young children will need different storage from a
    small apartment used by one or two adults. A pet-friendly home may need washable baskets
    and easy access to throws, while a media-heavy room may need better cable and device
    storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Storage works best when it supports the room's real routines, not an ideal version of the
    room that does not match daily life.
  </p>

  <h2>Use baskets for quick reset storage</h2>
  <p>
    Baskets are one of the simplest living room storage products. They work well because they
    make it easy to reset the room quickly.
  </p>
  <p>Useful basket storage ideas include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>A basket for blankets.</li>
    <li>A basket for children's toys.</li>
    <li>A basket for pet toys.</li>
    <li>A basket for magazines or books.</li>
    <li>A basket for cushions or throws.</li>
    <li>A small basket for remotes and chargers.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Choose baskets that suit the room and are easy to move. Soft baskets can be useful around
    children, while woven or structured baskets may look better in a more styled living area.
  </p>
  <p>
    The main rule is to give each basket a clear purpose. Too many general baskets can become
    clutter holders rather than storage solutions.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose a TV unit with useful storage</h2>
  <p>
    The TV unit often becomes the main storage piece in the living room. A good TV unit should
    do more than hold the screen. It should help manage devices, remotes, cords, games, DVDs,
    books or other living room items.
  </p>
  <p>Useful features may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Closed cupboards.</li>
    <li>Open shelves for devices.</li>
    <li>Cable holes.</li>
    <li>Drawers.</li>
    <li>Adjustable shelves.</li>
    <li>Enough width for the TV.</li>
    <li>A style that suits the rest of the room.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Closed storage is useful for items that look messy, such as spare cables, gaming
    controllers, manuals and small electronics. Open shelves are useful for devices that need
    airflow, such as consoles or media boxes.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, check the size carefully. A TV unit that is too small can make the room
    feel unbalanced, while one that is too large can reduce walking space.
    For a fuller checklist, see the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/tv-unit-and-media-storage-what-to-measure-before-you-buy/">TV unit and media storage guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep remotes and chargers in one place</h2>
  <p>
    Small items are often what make a living room feel cluttered. Remotes, phone chargers,
    headphones, glasses, coasters and small electronics can quickly spread across coffee
    tables and side tables.
  </p>
  <p>Useful options include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>A small tray.</li>
    <li>A remote holder.</li>
    <li>A drawer in the coffee table.</li>
    <li>A small lidded box.</li>
    <li>A side-table basket.</li>
    <li>A charging station.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A tray works well because it keeps small items grouped without hiding them completely. If
    the living room is shared, choose one obvious place for remotes so they are easier to
    find.
  </p>
  <p>
    For affiliate product placement later, this section could include remote organisers,
    cable clips, charging docks and small storage trays.
  </p>

  <h2>Consider a coffee table with storage</h2>
  <p>
    A coffee table can be useful, but it can also become a clutter magnet. If storage is
    limited, a coffee table with drawers, shelves or a lift-top design may be worth
    considering.
  </p>
  <p>Storage coffee tables can hold:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Remotes.</li>
    <li>Coasters.</li>
    <li>Magazines.</li>
    <li>Board games.</li>
    <li>Laptop accessories.</li>
    <li>Small toys.</li>
    <li>Spare chargers.</li>
    <li>Notebooks.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A lift-top coffee table may suit homes where the living room is also used for laptop work
    or casual meals. A simple shelf underneath can work well for baskets or books.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the room is small, choose a coffee table that does not block movement. Round or oval
    designs can be easier to move around in tight spaces. If the table also needs to sit on a
    rug, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-rug-size-and-placement-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">living room rug size guide</a>{" "}
    can help you check the seating zone before buying.
  </p>

  <h2>Use side tables deliberately</h2>
  <p>
    Side tables are useful beside sofas and armchairs, but they should not become dumping
    spots. A side table with a drawer or lower shelf can provide storage without taking up
    much space.
  </p>
  <p>Good uses for side-table storage include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Reading glasses.</li>
    <li>Books.</li>
    <li>Tissues.</li>
    <li>Chargers.</li>
    <li>TV remotes.</li>
    <li>Small baskets.</li>
    <li>Coasters.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If there is no room for a side table, a slim sofa table, wall shelf or small floor basket
    may be enough.
  </p>
  <p>
    The best side table is one that supports the way the seat is used. A reading chair may
    need space for a lamp and book. A sofa used for TV may need remotes and drink coasters
    nearby. For a more detailed comparison, see the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/side-tables-coffee-tables-and-console-tables-what-to-compare-before-you-buy/">living-room tables guide</a>.
    If lighting is the main reason for adding a table, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-lighting-ideas-for-australian-homes/">living room lighting guide</a>{" "}
    can help with lamp placement and power points.
  </p>

  <h2>Store blankets and throws neatly</h2>
  <p>
    Blankets and throws make a living room more comfortable, but they can look messy if they
    are left across every chair or sofa.
  </p>
  <p>Useful storage options include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Blanket baskets.</li>
    <li>Storage ottomans.</li>
    <li>Sofa-end baskets.</li>
    <li>Ladder racks.</li>
    <li>Drawers in a TV unit.</li>
    <li>A dedicated shelf.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A storage ottoman can be especially useful in small living rooms because it can work as
    seating, a footrest and hidden storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    If pets use the sofa, washable throws are often practical. Keep one or two accessible and
    store extras away so the room does not feel overloaded.
  </p>

  <h2>Create toy storage that is easy to use</h2>
  <p>
    In family homes, toys often end up in the living room even when there is a separate
    bedroom or play area. This is normal. The key is to make toy storage easy enough that
    children and adults can use it quickly.
  </p>
  <p>Useful toy storage ideas include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Low baskets.</li>
    <li>Cube storage.</li>
    <li>Storage ottomans.</li>
    <li>Lidded tubs.</li>
    <li>Rotating toy baskets.</li>
    <li>Small shelves for books.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid overcomplicating toy storage in the living room. If it takes too long to sort, it
    probably will not be used consistently.
  </p>
  <p>
    A simple system might be one basket for everyday toys and another place for books or
    puzzles. Extra toys can be rotated from another room if needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about pet storage</h2>
  <p>
    Pets often use the living room as much as people do. Pet toys, beds, blankets, grooming
    brushes and leads can all end up in the space.
  </p>
  <p>Useful pet storage may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>A toy basket.</li>
    <li>A washable pet bed.</li>
    <li>A basket for pet blankets.</li>
    <li>A small container for grooming tools.</li>
    <li>Hooks near the entry for leads.</li>
    <li>A storage bench near the door.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Choose washable storage where possible. Pet items collect fur, dust and odours, so fabric
    baskets and beds should be easy to clean.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the living room is small, avoid spreading pet products across several areas. One clear
    pet zone is usually easier to manage.
  </p>

  <h2>Use shelving without overcrowding the room</h2>
  <p>
    Shelving can add storage and display space, but too many visible items can make a living
    room feel busier.
  </p>
  <p>Good shelving uses include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Books.</li>
    <li>Plants.</li>
    <li>Baskets.</li>
    <li>Photo frames.</li>
    <li>Board games.</li>
    <li>Decorative objects.</li>
    <li>Small storage boxes.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Closed cabinets are better for items that do not look tidy. Open shelves work best when
    they have some empty space and a limited mix of items.
  </p>
  <p>
    In rentals, freestanding bookshelves may be easier than wall-mounted shelves. If using
    tall furniture, check whether it should be secured safely, especially in homes with
    children or pets.
  </p>

  <h2>Manage cables and power boards</h2>
  <p>
    Cables can make even a tidy living room look messy. TV units, lamps, chargers, speakers,
    consoles and routers can create a lot of visual clutter.
  </p>
  <p>Useful cable management options include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Cable clips.</li>
    <li>Cable sleeves.</li>
    <li>Cable boxes.</li>
    <li>Velcro ties.</li>
    <li>Cord covers.</li>
    <li>Labelled cables.</li>
    <li>Power boards with enough outlets.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Keep power boards accessible enough to use safely, but not sitting in the middle of the
    floor. Avoid overloading power points and check that cords are not running through
    walkways.
  </p>
  <p>
    A simple cable clean-up can make a living room feel more organised without buying new
    furniture.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep entry clutter out of the living room</h2>
  <p>
    In some homes, the front door opens directly into the living room. Shoes, bags, keys, mail
    and school items can quickly land on the sofa or floor.
  </p>
  <p>Useful entry storage may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>A small console table.</li>
    <li>Hooks.</li>
    <li>Shoe baskets.</li>
    <li>Key trays.</li>
    <li>Mail organisers.</li>
    <li>Storage benches.</li>
    <li>A basket for bags.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If there is no separate entryway, create a small drop zone near the door. This helps stop
    everyday items from spreading across the living room.
  </p>

  <h2>What to check before buying living room storage</h2>
  <p>Before buying living room storage products, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>The size of the room.</li>
    <li>Walking paths.</li>
    <li>Sofa and TV placement.</li>
    <li>Whether storage needs to be hidden or visible.</li>
    <li>Whether children or pets use the room.</li>
    <li>Whether the item is easy to clean.</li>
    <li>Whether it solves a real daily problem.</li>
    <li>Whether it will still be useful in six months.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Living room storage should make the room easier to use, not just add more furniture.
  </p>

  <h2>Final thoughts</h2>
  <p>
    A well-organised living room does not need to look perfect. It should feel easy to live
    in, easy to reset and comfortable for the people who use it every day.
  </p>
  <p>
    Start with the clutter that appears most often. That might be toys, blankets, remotes, pet
    items, cables or entryway clutter. Give those items a clear place to go, then improve the
    room one practical storage area at a time.
  </p>

